Q1 C. Shell Script for Port Scan using NetCat
================================================================================

SETUP (verify NetCat is installed):
-------------------------------------
   nc -h
   # If not installed:
   sudo apt install netcat-openbsd -y

SCRIPT (save as port_scan.sh):
--------------------------------
   #!/bin/bash
   # Port Scanner using NetCat
   # Usage: ./port_scan.sh

   # Target host (change as needed)
   host="www.example.com"

   # Prompt user for port range
   read -p "Enter starting port: " start_port
   read -p "Enter ending port: " end_port

   echo ""
   echo "Scanning $host from port $start_port to $end_port..."
   echo "-------------------------------------------"

   # Loop through each port in the range
   for (( port=start_port; port<=end_port; port++ ))
   do
       # nc flags: -z = scan only (no data), -v = verbose, -w1 = 1s timeout
       result=$(nc -zv -w1 "$host" "$port" 2>&1)

       if echo "$result" | grep -q "succeeded\|open\|Connected"; then
           echo "[OPEN]   Port $port"
       else
           echo "[CLOSED] Port $port"
       fi
   done

   echo "-------------------------------------------"
   echo "Scan complete."

SAVE AND RUN:
--------------
   chmod +x port_scan.sh
   ./port_scan.sh
   # Enter: start=79, end=82 (to test ports around HTTP)

FLAG REFERENCE:
----------------
   -z  : Zero-I/O mode — used for scanning, sends no data
   -v  : Verbose — prints connection success/failure messages
   -w1 : Timeout of 1 second per port (prevents hanging)
   2>&1: Redirects stderr to stdout so we can capture the output

