Q9 A. Scapy – ICMP Packet Monitor using Callback Function
================================================================================

HOW CALLBACKS WORK IN SCAPY:
------------------------------
The sniff() function accepts a prn parameter (short for "print/process").
This is a callback function automatically called for each matching packet.
Using filter="icmp" ensures only ICMP packets trigger the callback.

CODE (save as icmp_monitor.py):
---------------------------------
   from scapy.all import *

   # Step 1: Define the callback function
   # This function is called automatically for every captured ICMP packet
   def packet_callback(packet):
       # Ensure the packet has an IP layer before accessing IP fields
       if packet.haslayer(IP):
           src_ip = packet[IP].src
           dst_ip = packet[IP].dst

           if packet.haslayer(ICMP):
               icmp_type = packet[ICMP].type
               # ICMP type 8 = Echo Request (ping sent)
               # ICMP type 0 = Echo Reply  (ping response)
               type_name = "Echo Request" if icmp_type == 8 else \
                           "Echo Reply"   if icmp_type == 0 else \
                           f"Type {icmp_type}"

               print(f"[ICMP] {src_ip} → {dst_ip} | {type_name}")

   # Step 2: Start sniffing with the callback
   # filter="icmp"  → Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF) to capture only ICMP
   # store=0        → Don't store packets in RAM (saves memory for long runs)
   # prn=...        → Callback function for each packet
   print("ICMP Monitor started. Press Ctrl+C to stop.")
   print("Run 'ping 8.8.8.8' in another terminal to test.\n")

   sniff(filter="icmp", prn=packet_callback, store=0)

RUN:
----
Terminal 1:
   sudo python3 icmp_monitor.py

Terminal 2 (to generate ICMP traffic):
   ping 8.8.8.8

EXPECTED OUTPUT:
   [ICMP] 192.168.1.5 → 8.8.8.8     | Echo Request
   [ICMP] 8.8.8.8     → 192.168.1.5 | Echo Reply
   [ICMP] 192.168.1.5 → 8.8.8.8     | Echo Request
   ...

